      }
    ],
    "http://schema.org/name": [
      {
        "@value": "Taking on Water"
      }
    ],
    "http://schema.org/description": [
      {
        "@value": "<p>'Taking on Water' is a musical play: a work of words, music and movement telling spellbinding stories about climate, starting from the perspective of small coastal communities around Newfoundland and Labrador. Award-winning actor and playwright Robert Chafe interviewed residents of these communities about the challenges and rewards of living near and making a living from a changing ocean.  Chafe then chose a magic realist style to create stories which highlight the current environmental tensions we all experience, to create universally compelling images of: '...the town swallowed by a monster, the city buried by a storm. The village built on blue glass. And a place that just simply vanished. . .' </p>\n\n<p>These stories are told/performed by Robert and St. John's-based dancer and storyteller Louise Moyes, with music performed by Duo Concertante, written for them by acclaimed Winnipeg composer Randolph Peters.  All the creators/performers worked together to create an imaginative, yes sometimes funny, always powerful and evocative theatrical and musical journey.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"
      }
    ],
